# Which Codec Is Right for You?
In some instances there is a right or wrong choice in using one codec over another. But most of the time, it really depends on the business requirements. Here are <mark>some considerations to help you in making a codec decision:</mark>
### What do my endpoints support? 
Cisco phones support G.711 and G.729. Newer phones also support the iLBC codec. So in Cisco environments you are going to use one of these three.
### How many DSP channels will I need? 
DSP chips contain multiple channels with which to handle codec transcoding. If you find yourself having to constantly transcode one codec into another, you probably made a poor codec decision. DSP resources are not cheap. <mark>If you can limit transcoding, you should.</mark>
### How much voice quality do I need? 
Depending on your users and the environment they are used in, voice quality may or may not be a major factor in your decision-making process. A tried but true method of determining the quality of the audio of a voice codec is called the <mark>__Mean Opinion Score (MOS)__</mark>. Developed by the ITU, <mark>this quality-measurement system rates the quality of voice streams for a particular codec.It is actually very nonscientific, because the MOS is an average “opinion” of a group of people who listen to the same sentence for each codec tested. These listeners then rank the voice quality on a scale of 1 to 5.</mark>  A score of 1 is the worst quality, and a score of 5 is excellent quality.
